(Courtesy Roberto Gonzalez/Maker Faire Orlando) By Patrick Connolly | pconnolly@orlandosentinel.com | Orlando Sentinel PUBLISHED: November 5, 2024 at 5:00 AM EST Artists, makers, creators and craftspeople of all ages and backgrounds will congregate this weekend for the ‚ÄúGreatest Show and Tell on Earth.‚Äù Back for its 12th year in Central Florida Nov. 9-10, Maker Faire Orlando draws an estimated 14,000 attendees for two full days of power racing, cosplayers, battling robots, music and more than 250 exhibits with plenty of hands-on activities. ‚ÄúMaker Faire Orlando is a gathering of fascinating, curious people who enjoy learning and love sharing what they can do,‚Äù said Ian Cole, the Orlando event‚Äôs founder, in a news release. ‚ÄúFrom engineers to artists to scientists to crafters, Maker Faire Orlando is a venue for these ‚Äòmakers‚Äô to show their hobbies, experiments, or projects for others to glimpse the future and get inspired.‚Äù Justin ‚ÄúSKIP‚Äù Skipper is one such creator who hopes to inspire visitors at this weekend‚Äôs event. The Central Florida-based artist and muralist will have faire attendees contribute to one of three 8-by-8-foot murals that use a ‚Äúpaint by number‚Äù format. ‚ÄúBy the end of the show, we‚Äôll have three Maker Faire-themed murals that were painted by the maker community,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúWhat I‚Äôm doing this year is allowing people into an environment where they can contribute a little bit and feel like they actually had a part of something that is bigger.‚Äù Other event highlights include Robot Ruckus with combat robots, a drone zone, cosplay makers and power racing, an event where makers race their handmade machines with a budget of up to $500. The goal is to peel back the curtain on how things are made, perhaps motivating young creators to make their own inventions. ‚ÄúA big part of Maker Faire is to be able to create that ‚Äòwow‚Äô experience that really sparks imagination. We hope to inspire people to learn more, to get involved more and to find a way to be an inventor and a creator,‚Äù Skipper said. ‚ÄúIt is definitely about trying to inspire the next generation of creators and engineers.‚Äù If you go Maker Faire Orlando is open 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Nov. 9-10 at 4603 W. Colonial Drive in Orlando. Online advance tickets are $20 for adults and $15 for students and children ages 3-17 (before tax). Two-day passes are also available. Parking is free. Food is available on-site. More information: makerfaireorlando.com Fire heats up the Kinetic Field Stage at EDC Orlando, the Electric Daisy Carnival, at Tinker Field on Friday, Nov. 8, 2019. The festival returns Nov. 8-10. (Patrick Connolly/Orlando Sentinel) More weekend events The¬†Maitland Rotary Art Festival returns to Lake Lily Park for the 48th annual event. Explore work from 145 artists during the free-admission event from 5-9 p.m. Nov. 8, 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Nov. 9 and 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Nov. 10 at 701 Lake Lily Drive in Maitland. More information: maitlandartfest.org EDC Orlando is back with tens of thousands of attendees gathering at Tinker Field for a weekend full of electronic dance music, carnival rides and high-production stages. General admission starts at $132.14 for a single day or $264.34 for a three-day pass. The festival is open from 1 p.m.-midnight Nov. 8-10 at 287 S. Tampa Ave. in Orlando. More information: orlando.electricdaisycarnival.com Casselberry‚Äôs annual Craft Beer & Blues Festival lands at Lake Concord Park, featuring performer Pat Travers. Visitors can also find food trucks, art exhibits and vendors at the free event, which takes place from 5-9 p.m. Nov. 9 at 95 Triplet Lake Drive in Casselberry. More information: casselberry.org College Park Jazz Fest is back for its annual tradition with 12 live bands performing jazz, R&B and rock music. The annual neighborhood block party also features food vendors and shopping. Tickets are $15 per person in advance or $20 during the day of the event. Children 12 and younger enter for free. The festival is from 5-11 p.m. Nov. 9 along Edgewater Drive. More information: collegeparkmainstreet.com Find me @PConnPie on Instagram or send me an email: pconnolly@orlandosentinel.com . Admission is FREE. Proceeds benefit local charities and non-profits.¬†For more information, visit http://maitlandrotaryartfestival.org/. If you or your organization are interested in getting more involved, please contact Festival Chair Pat Woodley at 407.777.8515 or email MaitlandRotary@gmail.com.¬†Ways to Support the Maitland Rotary Art Festival | Art Under the Stars (R): (1) Sponsorships are still available between $1,000 and $15,000; (2) Become a Patron of the Arts for $300 or $500 to receive Art Vouchers to purchase art at the festival, Patron Party invitations and more; (3) Advertise in our Festival Program for as little as $125 for a Business Card Ad up to $1,000 for the glossy back cover; (4) Become a Festival Volunteer; (5) Publicize our Art Festival by posting our mini-posters and flyers; (6) Attend the Art Festival Nov 12-14 with family and friends. The Latest News The 48th Annual Maitland Rotary Art Festival is back with art, music, activities, food and more! Alastair Mac Nov 8, 2024 2 min read This weekend, enjoy another year of fantastic art, lively music, and family fun at Lake Lily Park in Maitland! The 48th Annual Maitland Rotary Art Festival returns to Lake Lily Park in Maitland this weekend, featuring dozens of the best traveling artists, together with live music, activities for the kids, food, and more. This years event kicks off with a patrons party on Thursday, November 7, with the festiva open Friday, Nov. 8 from 5 - 9 pm, Saturday, Nov. 9 10 am - 7 pm, and Sunday, Nov. 10 from 10 am - 4 pm. Discover all the latest events and festival happening throughout Central Florida. The Maitland Rotary Art Festival has been entertaining Central Florida residents and visitors since 1976. Hosted annually by the Rotary Club of Maitland, Florida, the event has evolved into a community celebration of the arts. The many public and private partnerships make it possible for Maitland Rotarians to give back to our community.
